<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cynosurus echinatus </i>is a non-native annual grass from Europe and has a Cal-IPC rating of Moderate. Seeds germinate in the fall and plants survive the winter as small seedlings. Plants flower early the following spring and set seed in early summer. They produce a large number of seeds that do not persist in a seed bank (Clark and Wilson 2001, DiTomaso and Healy 2007).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Arrhenatherum elatius </i>is a non-native perennial grass, from Europe. Basal stems may have bulbous internodes that can propagate vegetatively. Plants have been grown as forage, and they readily escape in meadows and disturbed areas (Flora of North America 2021). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance occur on moderately warm exposures in areas where annual precipitation tends to be > 8 cm and temperature is relatively low, especially compared to many other annual grass types. <i>C. echinatus </i>is also common in the understory in low-elevation hardwood and conifer woodlands in the mountains of northern California (Klein et al. 2007). However, most information about this type comes from the northern Coast Ranges, where these two non-native grasses among others have been increasing and invading many areas formerly dominated by native grasses. Other mesic non-native grasses have been documented invading coastal bunchgrass prairies, such as <i>Nassella manicata</i> and <i>Danthonia pilosa (= Rytidosperma penicillatum)</i> (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021), and are included in this alliance.<br/>
<br/>
Current vegetation studies assign stands to semi-natural stands categories only if they have high nonnative cover, and few natives are present at low cover (see Chapter 7). Jimerson et al. (2000) defined two series (of <i>Arrhenatherum elatius </i>and <i>Cynosurus echinatus </i>), which we have since combined together, with associations based on overall species composition. Some 27% of their plots lacked native grasses; the remainder had at least one native grass species present. Using the membership rules of recent surveys (e.g., Klein et al. 2007), we would place some of their stands in the <i>Festuca californica - Danthonia californica, Bromus carinatus - Elymus glaucus, </i>and other grassland alliances if we could make stand-by-stand individual determinations. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
