    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Cynosurus echinatus</i> includes Central California Coast (261A), Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), Northern California Coast (263A), Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261F), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262Ba-Bb).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-u). Stands in the section have <i>Avena fatua, Bromus hordeaceus, Lotus micranthus,</i> and <i>Taraxacum officinale </i>(Jimerson et al. 2000).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). Stands occurring coastally include a variety of non-native herbs, such as <i>Avena, Danthonia pilosa, Hypochaeris radicata, Linum bienne, Nassella manicata, Plantago lanceolata, </i>and <i>Rumex acetosella. </i>(Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Klein et al. 2015). They have invaded native stands of <i>Danthonia californica, Festuca idahoensis, Elymus glaucus, Nassella pulchra, Lotus,</i>among other herbs.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). Pure and mixed stands from throughout the section (Jimerson et al. 2000) depict the type. They recognized six stand types differing in species composition, litter cover and thickness, elevation, coarse fragments, slope, annual temperature, and precipitation. Native plants found in the survey included <i>Achnatherum lemmonii, Bromus carinatus, Danthonia californica, Elymus glaucus, Eschscholzia californica, Hemizonia congesta, Lotus micranthus, Lupinus bicolor, </i>and <i>Madia </i>spp. Non-native plants included <i>Aira caryophyllea, Avena </i>spp<i>.</i>, <i>Bromus hordeaceus, B. tectorum, Erodium </i>spp., <i>Poa pratensis, Rumex acetosella, Taeniatherum caput-medusae, </i>and <i>Taraxacum officinale.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). The Jimerson et al. (2000) survey included some samples from this section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-b). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Sawyer (2006) discussed the historic role of Native American burning, ranching, and restoration practices in the Bald Hill prairies of the northern Coast Ranges, many currently dominated by <i>Arrhenatherum elatius, Cynosurus echinatus, </i>and other non-natives. </i>According to Jimerson et al. (2000), the presence of <i>C. echinatus </i>indicates range deterioration because the grass matures later than most annual grasses, tolerates early and heavy grazing, and develops high cover when other plants have low cover. They place its disturbance indicator value as immediately between <i>Bromus hordeaceus </i>(highest) and <i>Arrhenatherum elatius </i>(lowest), suggesting that most stands have an intermediate level of grazing, fire, and other short-term disturbances compared to other annual grasslands in northwest California. Some stands of <i>C. echinatus </i>do, however, contain <i>Centaurea solstitialis, Hypericum perforatum, </i>and <i>Taeniatherum caput-medusae, </i>which CDFA (2003) considers noxious weeds, also suggesting poor range conditions. 

Stands strongly dominated by <i>A. elatius </i>and/or <i>C. echinatus </i>often have plants of conservation value since they have invaded areas formerly dominated by native species, e.g. <i>Danthonia californica, Festuca idahoensis, </i>as well as rare species such as <i>Astragalus agnicidus </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) and <i>Tracyina rostrata </i>(a CNPS list 1B.2 plant). Restoration activities can include prescribed grazing, summer to fall burning, post-fire herbicide application, and other techniques to reduce the impacts of the non-natives (Arguello 1994, Jimerson et al. 2000). However, the non-native annual <i>C. echinatus </i>has low moisture content by mid-summer, as compared to other non-native and native grasses, whereby some non-native species have the capacity to alter fire behavior by either increasing or decreasing fire intensity and rare of spread, which can complicate restoration of the fire-dependent native grasslands and oak woodlands (Linvingston and Varner 2016). </div>
</div>

    

    

